I'm selling my Beretta PX4 and CX4 Storm kit. They are both in near condition, with nothing wrong at all.
If you aren’t familiar with the Storm platform, they are both excellent Beretta products. The Italians wanted a robust carbine that could share ammo/magazines with a pistol, with both weapons being friendly to left and right handed shooters. So Beretta started developing a carbine/pistol to meet those requirements, and they did a spectacular job at it!
So here’s what you will be getting. Both a pistol and rifle chambered in 9MM, with (5) 17 round magazines, they are both very reliable, accurate, and absolutely bulletproof.
About the PX4 Storm Pistol - It’s a full size 9MM pistol, with a proven rotating barrel design that is extremely accurate. It has a safety/decocker mounted on the slide (like a Beretta 92) and has a reversible magazine release for fully ambidextrous manipulation. It’s in near mint condition, with just the common usage wear marks. The bore is bright and shiny, and is in perfect mechanical working condition.
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beretta_Px4_Storm
About the CX4 Storm Carbine - It’s also chambered in 9MM, and comes with a full rail on top for optics, and 3 forward rails, for lights/foregrips. It has a very good EOTech clone on it that works well, holds a zero, is non-parallax. The charging handle, and ejection port, and mag release  are reversible for fully ambidextrous manipulation. This is a very smooth shooting, super reliable, and extremely accurate carbine capable of, 200+ yard engagement with iron sights as seen in this video.
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rjYYrCzmCRA
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beretta_Cx4_Storm
You get everything you see in the pictures. That’s a PX4 9MM pistol, CX4 9MM carbine, (6) 17 round magazines etc. First one with $1800.00 cash OBO takes them. If you are looking for the ultimate pistol/carbine combination, this is it. I don’t know of any other guns by any other maker that offers this kind of flexibility, versatility, reliability, or ambidextrous manipulation to this level!

Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  RARE S&W Prewar Non-Registered Magnum
postcontent: VERY RARE Prewar Smith & Wesson Non-Registered .357 Magnum Revolver W/4” Barrel & Ivory Grips, Mfg. 1940. Stock # MSH251416SP. Serial # 608xx. One of over a thousand Antique and Modern Collectible firearms, including Military, Sporting, Custom and Tactical guns, as well as Edged Weapons and Militaria we have for sale at Jackson Armory (see our other listings),This is a VERY RARE Smith & Wesson Pre-War Non-Registered .357 Magnum Revolver. Per “Standard Catalog of Smith & Wesson” (Page 134-135) by Supica and Nahas, the definitive modern book on S&W history, the Prewar Non-Registered Magnums are even more rare than the Registered Magnums. Here is what they have to say: “These are even more rare than the Registered Magnum Models, with only about 1400 produced between 1935-1941. In general, they were more likely to be heavily used than the Registereds.” They go on to say that non-standard barrel lengths command substantial premiums. This gun has a non-standard, 4” barrel (see the aforementioned book for the standard barrel lengths). It has been re-finished in nickel, and it has a magnificent set of ivory grips, the left grip is a hand-cut steer-head grip. Per the serial number, this gun was produced in 1940. Although the “SMITH & WESSON” marking on the left side of the barrel is somewhat obscured by the re-finish, all other markings and the S&W logo on the receiver are crisp and legible. The grips have aged and yellowed a bit, but they have no cracks and they look great (that are also worth several hundred dollars in their own right!). The finish has many service marks, and overall condition is about 85-90%. The revolver has a shiny bore with fairly strong rifling, and double-action trigger pull is smooth. These guns were used by Lawmen, and used heavily, as per the book. Famous Handgunners like Bill Jordan and Skeeter Skelton loved these guns and wrote a lot about them. We can say with almost certainty that if you obtain a Smith & Wesson Factory Letter, it will add value to this already RARE pistol – especially if it was delivered to a Police Agency, or even to Wolf & Klar in Ft Worth (that would account for the ivory grips!). title: For Sale:  SAVAGE AXIS XP,  223 REM BOLT ACTION RIFLE MODEL 19228, Bushnell 3-9x40 Scope
location: Spring Hill call John @ 727-460-3131, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
The Savage Arms Company was organized in 1894 by Arthur Savage in Utica, New York. A native of Jamaica, Arthur led a romantic life, having been schooled in England and the United States. In his thirties, he explored the interior of Australia and was held captive for a year by Aborigines. Later, he became the owner of the largest cattle ranch in Australia.

After moving to Utica, New York, he developed the Savage Halpine torpedo, became the Superintendent of the Utica Belt Line Railroad, and invented the first "hammerless" lever action rifle with the entire mechanism enclosed in a steel receiver. This remarkable rifle featured a rotary magazine with a unique counter that visually displayed the number of bullets remaining in the receiver. The Model 99, as it became known, advanced firearm technology, offered the average person an affordable rifle, and started a business that has stood the test of time. In 1919, Chief Lame Deer (above) approached Arthur to purchase lever-action rifles for the Indian reservation and the two men struck a deal. The tribe would get discounted rifles and Savage would get their support and endorsement. It was at this time in the company's history, that Arthur Savage added the Indian head logo--a direct gift from the Chief--to the company name. By 1919, Savage Arms was manufacturing high power rifles, 22 caliber rifles, pistols and ammunition.
